# Default style

This is the default Style.texture for Texture article revision. It shapes
voice, structure, and citation shape. It is a toolbar-only source entity: it
appears in the source toolbar but is not cited in the document body because it
is a control input, not a content source.

## Article format

Write a coherent article with clear information hierarchy. Do not default to
Q&A format, a Source Brief, Working Revision, Evidence Gathering note, outline,
or placeholder. The document head after a revision must be publishable article
prose or an explicit correction/update draft.

## Citation shape

Use `insert_source_ref` after the supported sentence or clause. The default
display mode is `numbered_ref`: a collapsed inline citation point that expands
to reveal the source title and excerpt.

Use `display_mode: expanded_ref` only when a long excerpt or media item should
appear as an expanded block next to the claim it supports. The reader can
collapse an expanded_ref back to the numbered citation point; that toggle is
local reader UI state and does not mutate the canonical document.

## Immaterial sources

If a source is immaterial (a duplicate, a dead lead, a source that no longer
supports a distinct claim), call `mark_source_unused` with the source_entity_id
and a short rationale. The source stays in the toolbar but does not need a body
`source_ref`. No source is silently ignored.

## Media sources

Media sources (YouTube, images, PDFs, audio) are cited with `insert_source_ref`
like any other source. The display mode (`numbered_ref` or `expanded_ref`) is an
editorial choice: expanded_ref when the media should appear as a visible block,
numbered_ref when an inline citation point suffices. The reader can toggle
between the two states.
